2026-05-07 | Maximum Reachable Value Through Valid Jumps

Question
Return ans[i] = maximum reachable value from i.
	Key Observation
If there exists any larger value reachable indirectly,
eventually you can keep moving toward larger elements.
The important insight:
		all indices connected through valid jumps
		form connected components.
And:
		every element in a component can reach
		the maximum element of that component.
Now observe:
- if there exists a smaller element to the right,
  you can jump there
- then from there potentially jump left to larger values
This effectively connects indices across ranges.
The reachable maximum for an index becomes:
		the maximum value in its connected region.
	Approach
1.	Build connected components implicitly:
		adjacent indices with different values
		become mutually reachable through chains.
2.	Using monotonic behavior:
		all indices in same connected segment
		share the same maximum reachable value.
3.	We process components using DFS/BFS.
	Time Complexity
	O(n)
	Space Complexity
	O(n)
	Solution
class Solution {
public:
    vector<int> maxValue(vector<int>& nums) {
        
        int n = nums.size();

        vector<int> ans(n);
        vector<int> pref(n);

        // Build prefix maximum array
        pref[0] = nums[0];

        for(int i = 1; i < n; i++) {
            pref[i] = max(pref[i - 1], nums[i]);
        }

        int suffMin = INT_MAX;

        // Traverse from right to left
        for(int i = n - 1; i >= 0; i--) {

            if(pref[i] > suffMin) {
                ans[i] = (i + 1 < n) ? ans[i + 1] : pref[i];
            }
            else {
                ans[i] = pref[i];
            }

            suffMin = min(suffMin, nums[i]);
        }

        return ans;
    }
};
	Key Insight
The problem is fundamentally:
		reachability in a directed graph  
Each valid jump forms a directed edge.  
Then for every node:
		find maximum-valued reachable node.
